Detect user navigating away, don't interpret as ajax error

Whenever a user navigates away, all ajax calls will fail with the same
result like a cross-domain redirect (SSO). To distinguish these cases,
we need to detect whether the error is a result of the user navigating
away. For this, we introduce a new flag that will be set in
"beforeunload".

Additional handling was required for false positives in case "beforeunload" is
used (ex: cancelled upload) and the user cancelled the navigation.

Switch python indentation from 2-space to 4-space (#1145)

pep8 specifies 4 space indentation.  The use of 2 spaces is, I believe,
a historical anomaly where certain large organizations such as google
chose 2 over 4 and have yet to make the switch.

For a project like wabt with little python code I think the cost of
switching is small enough to justify the churn.

drop the client connection when a request causes an error

Fixes trello#41 https://trello.com/c/sFSHvH2a

* when a request fails, chances are high that some game objects are
  in an inconsistent state as a result (see Trello card for details);
  therefore, forcing the client to reload by closing the connection
  seems like the safest course of action
* send a server message (action CLOSE) before disconnecting the client
  (with a custom message "REQ_PROC_ERROR", which is unknown to the
  client but at least causes it not to reconnect immediately)
* "roll back" the modifications made by the request by not persisting
  them and clearing the respective objects from the live object cache
  (forcing them to be reloaded on the next access)

add graceful shutdown logic

* add shutdown code to all the modules where it is necessary (in
  particular, close client sessions and flush the persistence cache)
* send 0 to statsd for all gauges modified during the process lifetime

Remove stack_overflow error workaround

(no longer necessary with current node.js/io.js)

Process requests sequentially (per client)

* process requests from the same client in strict FIFO order (except
  special cases like `ping`); request processing may be interrupted
  due to fibers/wait.for, this prevents handling a request while a
  previous one from the same client has not been completed yet
* minor test code refactoring (move `getTestSession` function to
  helpers module)

Encapsulate request queueing in dedicated class

Refactor sequential request queueing/processing into a separate
`RequestQueue` class, which might later be assigned to game objects
(locations and groups) to emulate the original GS's threading model.
Besides that, it could potentially allow using one Fiber per request
queue (instead of per single request), for better efficiency and less
thread-safety-like issues due to concurrent Fibers.

Process all relevant operations in request queues

* replace all occurrences of `RequestContext.run` calls (RPCs, game
  object timers, etc) with the equivalent function pushed into the
  appropriate request queue
* use a generic options object to supply various flags/args to `rq.push`

Less verbose log output

* make log output more compact by reducing the amount of metadata
  included in most messages (only ID or brief tag for session/request
  queue/request context, instead of complex objects)
